(2 pt) because they are taken from a poll of samples of a population, not a poll of the entire population.

Exercise 2: (4 points)

(2 pt) In order to generalize the report’s findings, we must assume that the sampling method was random and representative of the population as a whole.

(2 pt) This is not a reasonable assumption. The polls are only drawn from 57 of the 196 countries in existence today. Page 11 shows that some people are also less likely to say whether or not they are atheist.

Exercise 4: (4 points)

(2 pt) Some reasonable code for calculating proportions

(2 pt) The number above agrees with Table 6 in the report, which reports 5%.

us12 <- atheism %>%
  filter(nationality == "United States", year == "2012")
  
us12 %>%
  group_by(response) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(prop = round(n / sum(n), 2))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   response        n  prop
##   <fct>       <int> <dbl>
## 1 atheist        50  0.05
## 2 non-atheist   952  0.95

Exercise 5: (12 points)

  • Independence:
    • (2 pt) We are not told whether sampling was random or not.
    • (2 pt) 1002 < 10% of all US population
    • (2 pt) Assuming sampling was random, we can assume that the response of one individual in the sample is independent of another.
  • Success-failure:
    • (2 pt) 50 observed successes, and 952 observed failures, both greater than 10.

(2 pt) Since both conditions are met, we can assume that the sampling distribution of atheists in the US is nearly normal.

(2 pt) We are not so confident in the independence condition.

NOTE: we can be somewhat lenient about the random sampling part in the independence condition.

Exercise 6: (6 points)

(2 pt) Code

(2 pt) Correct output

(2 pt) ME = 0.0135

inference(y = response, data = us12, statistic = "proportion",
          type = "ci", method = "theoretical", success = "atheist")
## Single categorical variable, success: atheist
## n = 1002, p-hat = 0.0499
## 95% CI: (0.0364 , 0.0634)

turkey12 <- atheism %>%
  filter(nationality == "Turkey", year == "2012")
turkey12 %>%
  group_by(response) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(prop = round(n / sum(n), 2))

##   <fct>       <int> <dbl>

          type = "ci", method = "theoretical", success = "atheist")

## n = 1032, p-hat = 0.0203
## 95% CI: (0.0117 , 0.029)

Exercise 8: (6 points)

(2 pt) As \(p\) increases, the margin of error increases, until \(p = 0.5\), and then as \(p\) increases \(ME\) also decreases.

(2 pt) Code for plot

(2 pt) Display of the plot

n <- 1000
p <- seq(0, 1, 0.01)
me <- 2 * sqrt(p * (1 - p)/n)
dd <- data.frame(p = p, me = me)
qplot(x = p, y = me, data = dd, 
      ylab = "Margin of Error", xlab = "Population Proportion")

More Practice (30 points)

13: (6 points)

spain <- atheism %>%
  filter(nationality == "Spain")
inference(y = response, x = factor(year), data = spain, null = 0, 
          statistic = "proportion", type = "ht", method = "theoretical", 
          success = "atheist", alternative = "twosided")
## Response variable: categorical (2 levels, success: atheist)
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_2005 = 1146, p_hat_2005 = 0.1003
## n_2012 = 1145, p_hat_2012 = 0.09
## H0: p_2005 =  p_2012
## HA: p_2005 != p_2012
## z = 0.8476
## p_value = 0.3966

14: (12 points - 6 points for HT, 6 points for CI)

us <- atheism %>%
  filter(nationality == "United States")
inference(y = response, x = factor(year), data = us, null = 0, 
          statistic = "proportion", type = "ht", method = "theoretical", 
          success = "atheist", alternative = "twosided")
## Response variable: categorical (2 levels, success: atheist)
## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_2005 = 1002, p_hat_2005 = 0.01
## n_2012 = 1002, p_hat_2012 = 0.0499
## H0: p_2005 =  p_2012
## HA: p_2005 != p_2012
## z = -5.2431
## p_value = < 0.0001

inference(y = response, x = factor(year), data = us, 
          statistic = "proportion", type = "ci", method = "theoretical", 
          success = "atheist")

## Explanatory variable: categorical (2 levels) 
## n_2005 = 1002, p_hat_2005 = 0.01
## n_2012 = 1002, p_hat_2012 = 0.0499
## 95% CI (2005 - 2012): (-0.0547 , -0.0251)
